04930nam a22006135i 9788367405065DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20222022pl     fo  d z      eng d  a9788367405065  a(DE-B1597)637696  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aplcPL 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aKunc, Josef, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThirty years of retail transformation in V4 countries /cJosef Kunc, Markéta Novotná, František Križan, Kristína Bilková, Tamás Sikos T., Dariusz Ilnicki, Ryan Wyeth. 1aWarsaw ;aBerlin : bSciendo, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (201 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContent -- t1 Thirty years of post-socialist retail transformation in Central Europe -- t2 The transformation of Czech retail -- t3 The transformation of Slovak retail -- t4 The transformation of Hungarian retail -- t5 The transformation of Poland retail -- t6 Socio-economic challenges in retailing: past experience and future perspectives -- t7 Details and differences in retail transformation in the V4 countries: Concluding comments -- tREFERENCES -- tABOUT AUTHORS -- tINDEX0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe book presents a comprehensive view of the development and transformation of retail in the Central European region, specifically in the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland and Hungary (so-called Visegrad Group countries, Visegrad Four or V4 countries). These countries have long-term common historical ties and culture. Their socialist history still united them by common economic and geopolitical interests. The aim of the book is to provide readers with a deeper insight into the retail environment of the V4 countries, which is linked to three decades of post-socialist transformation. This transformation has been associated with a fundamental change in the economic environment, localization strategies, and spatial distribution, creating a new network structure with new catchment and commuting links. It has also been associated with the development of large retail units and a fundamental change in shopping behaviour and consumer preferences of the affected populations by restricting purposeful shopping only and moving to entertainment and leisure in shopping centres. The book also reflects current trends in the use of smart technologies in shopping and responds to the impact of the Covid-19 pandemic on today's retail.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aretailing, retail structure, shopping centres, challenges, globalisation, Central Europe.1 aBilková, Kristína, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBilková, Kristína, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIlnicki, Dariusz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aIlnicki, Dariusz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrižan, František, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKrižan, František, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunc, Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovotná, Markéta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNovotná, Markéta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSikos T., Tamás, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSikos, Tamás T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWyeth, Ryan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.l